etical concern for crime victims in the criminal justice system, examins the variety of forms of legal and service provision inclusion, amd concludes by analysing the various needs of victims which continue to be unmet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aVictims of crimesxGovernment policyzIreland. 0aVictims of crimeszIreland. 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aEU Directive on Victims&apos.  aIrish criminal process.  aOmbudsman.  aRights.  aWitness Care Units.  acrime victim.  ahegemonic dominance.  ahuman rights.  amovement.  anational election issue.  aservice rights.  avictimology research.  avictims&apos.1 aKilcommins, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeahy, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLeahy, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpain, Eimear, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, Kathleen Moore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWalsh, Kathleen Moore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615372240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526153722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526153722/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles